<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-25T07:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-25T07:30:00-05:00" n="13" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d13">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793B.02/1–2551: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-25T18:00:00+05:30">January
                                    25, 1951—6 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1831. I outlined to Bajpai<note n="1" xml:id="d13fn1">Sir Girja Shanker
                                Bajpai, Secretary-General of the Indian Ministry of External
                                Affairs.</note> yesterday our current thinking re Tibet as set forth
                            in <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> attached to Depinstr 86 January
                                6.<note n="2" xml:id="d13fn2">Instruction 86, not printed,
                                transmitted a copy of an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> to the
                                British Embassy in Washington, dated December 30, 1950; for text of
                                the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>, see <ref target="frus1950v06#pg_612">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1950, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, p. 612</ref>.</note> Bajpai
                            expressed appreciation for this information and asked if I could give
                            him informal memorandum summarizing its contents. This I shall do.
                            Bajpai added <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> at present so immersed
                            in problem maintaining world peace it was giving little thought to
                            Tibet; in fact, he did not recall that Tibet was even mentioned during
                            recent Commonwealth Conference.<note n="3" xml:id="d13fn3">The Prime
                                Ministers of the British Commonwealth countries met in London during
                                the first part of January.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Henderson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>